(22, 'A day that we all have not forgotten...', 'It seems like forever ago when that strange thing happened to us. Some of us barely remember; Some of us don''t even know; and some of us chose to forget. Hi, I am Nat4an and I am here to talk about today being 9/11/12.[!--more--]\r\n\r\n<h2>The Story</h2>\r\n<p>It was a bright, beautiful day in the world of USA. New York to be exact. Many people were in a different mindset that day until the worst attack in US History happened. The World Trade Center was hit and now today there lies a memorial for the lost souls of that attack. For many people this came at a shock. A shock that rocked the everyday lives of the US Inhabitants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We now are heading into the 11th anniversary of 9/11 (what we called it at the time) and I for one am not going to give the full story here since I am not a journalist. To read the full story, I am sure you can google it. :) So what were you doing that day? I was a young, elementary student (kid) in 5th or 4th grade. I did not realize at the time what was happening because I was too young. But now that I have had the chance to grow up in a post-9/11 age, I realize something - there are many countries who hate how we have the freedom to do whatever we desire. Many countries would love to have that freedom and we as Americans take it for granted.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>How does that affect us now?</h2>\r\n<p>Right now we have a very important election coming up that could mean to some people the difference between life and death. We got, out of all the candidates, one candidate and current president attempting to decolonize America by bringing us into a socialistic government. IE. Putting the government in charge of everything which means limiting the freedom we have. The same freedom that rings and other countries wish they had. He tells us in a book entitled &quot;Dreams from My Father\r\n&quot; some ideas that come from his father about how America is so BIG, bad, and ugly and that things need to happen in order to change it. The change he was talking about in 2008 when he was elected.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Why am I writing about this?</h2>\r\n<p>I feel like I should write about this because this kind of story is considered memorable and old news but I for one want to keep it alive by doing what I can to honor my country and let those who don''t know or have forgotten the story that shook us to the core. If it weren''t for 9/11, we would be totally different today. Also, I like it that the date today is 9/11/12. A consecutively-sequenced date and I like consecutively-sequenced dates. In fact, I sleep with consecutively-sequenced dates. Okay, that is way too much information. Back on topic, I would also like to tell you to wake up. Yes, I already know you are awake but I mean look what the world is turning into and look how the government is trying to change us, change the very foundation our fore-fathers planted, change that WE REALLY DON''T NEED.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Closing remarks</h2>\r\nThank you for taking the time to read my blog post on 9/11/12 out of all the one-hundred-million other posts out there on the interwebs. I know that this entry may not get that many views, but this is more for a library collection that I am building - one blog at a time. I mean just look at the progress I made so far. If you don''t know where to look, you can start by checking out the &quot;Search Nat4an.com...&quot;. Go ahead and type in anything (any topic, word, phrase, etc) into it and see what I am talking about. That is the work of a true coding genius. One who takes the time, out of his busy developing schedule, to create a custom search for his entire web portfolio, after many painful hours of slaving away at a hot keyboard instead of going out and searching for a pre-built Custom Search  Engine and slapping it on the site and calling it a day - a process that most developers use in order to take the easy road, but this comes at a cost and that is the cost of showcasing your work to a potential employer or client. Of course, this blog entry is not quite the place to discuss this topic so I will continue closing this entry but I just wanted to point out what I had done, in the most reserved way, and let it serve as a prime example for this entire blog entry. Back to what I was concluding, that this is what America is suppose to be like. A place that is not lazy and does work to create jobs, develop things instead of taking from other places, and staying the way it has always been since the days of our ancestors. I leave you with this: what were you doing on 9/11 and how did it affect you? Take care and Nat4an signing off. Good day!', 1, 6, '911,blog,obama,thoughts,USA,anniversary,post 911,whats your story,freedom,election,Dreams from My Father,change we dont need,change,big,bad,ugly,custom search,built,work,lazy,developers,what were you doing on 911,', '2012-09-11 13:25:47', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 2012, '09', '11', '13', '25', '47', 'yes', 'Published', 'no', ''),
(23, 'RanAgram Tuesday Post 4', '<h2>In Game-related News</h2>\r\n<p>\r\n<a href="http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/09/11/james-cameron-on-writing-the-avatar-sequels" target="_blank">James Cameron on Writing the Avatar Sequels</a>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>My Feelings</h2>\r\n<p>\r\nAccomplished\r\n</p>\r\n[!--more--]\r\n<h2>New App I played with</h2>\r\n<p>\r\n<a href="http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/clear/id493136154?mt=8" target="_blank">Clear</a>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>New Friend</h2>\r\n<p>\r\n<a href="http://ipv6.statigr.am/childofthetardis" target="_blank">Alyssa Sisneros</a>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Today''s Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>\r\npirates from beyond\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>WotD</h2>\r\n<p>\r\nIndirection\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\nThanks again for a great random day! Have a blessed one and keep reading!', 1, 5, 'ahh,blessing,daily,day,general,general blog,general day info,my day,my day in general,nathan,ranagrams,clear,james cameron,titanic,avatar,accomplished,alyssa sisneros,', '2012-09-11 18:35:44', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 2012, '09', '11', '18', '35', '44', 'yes', 'Published', 'no', ''),
(24, 'Why you should use Google Chrome to design your website', '<p>Are you a web developer/designer? Do you need a testing platform to develop all your many web applications? Have you yourself ever wondered "What web browser should I use to design in?"? Have you ever stumbled across multiple websites that tell you to use this browser or that browser? If you answered yes to one or more of the following questions, then this article is for you!</p>[!--more--]\r\n\r\n<h1>The Basis of Web Design</h1>\r\n<p>Web Design is the design, rendering, building, creating, and developing model of the whole entire World Wide Web. Without design there is no creativity. Without creativity we all just look at blank, blan, ordinary, websites that will get us no where and do nothing for us. Through Web Design we can become the extraordinary and rise above competition to provide beautiful, elegantly-designed, multiplexes of gates to other realms and show prospective clients that we know what we are doing and we mean business.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nWeb Design requires a strong creative gene and a good eye for color. It is something that is shaping up to be something that is the backbone of the internet if it hasn''t already become that. Creativity makes the web more colorful and personal to the visitor.\r\n</p>\r\n<h1>My Approach</h1>\r\n<p>When it comes down to designing and building web applications and websites I like to use the simple 3-step process. First I write out pseudo-code of the webpage/website I am trying to make. Pseudo-code is a form of code that is when you write in basic english "this is going to do that, when you click this" sort of format. An alternative to pseudo-code is writing your website/webpage in plain basic HTML. This helps the designer to see their website before actually putting the functionality into it. Next step is to take the static code and make it dynamic by using PHP. This makes your sites more modular and easier to manage. Lastly, you will want to check <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_engine_optimization " target="_blank">Search Engine Optimization</a> (SEO) and Functionality of your code as well as check to see if your CSS (considering you put CSS in your page) is compatible across multiple web browsers (Firefox, Google Chrome, Internet Explorer (5, 6, 7, 8, and 9), Safari, Opera, and occasionally Netscape/Konqueror). And for the cases with different compatibility issues, you can create <a href="http://www.quirksmode.org/css/condcom.html" target="_blank">conditional CSS</a> (or <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/2012/WD-css3-conditional-20120911/ " target="_blank">here</a> or <a href="http://www.webmonkey.com/2010/02/browser-specific_css_hacks/ " target="_blank">here</a>) in your HTML files (because CSS does not let you put this conditional CSS in them directly or you can use a <a href="http://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/browser-specific-hacks/ " target="_blank">few hacks to make it easier</a> but I highly recommend not doing because it could be considered as "cutting corners". Only use hacks if you have exhausted every attempt to use conditional CSS and you are out of options).  Using Conditional CSS will direct the web browser to display the correct CSS style and hopefully put an end to this Web Designer''s nightmare.</p>\r\n<h1>Why do different browsers display pages different?</h1>\r\n<p>A browser is a program developed to display the contents of a web server in the form of a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG" target="_blank">WYSIWYG</a> method. So "Why do different browsers display pages differently?". That seems to the be the question that plagues the internet most of the time. A web browser displays code after being interpreted or rendered. It''s in that process of rendering or interpreting that the browser interprets the page in a unique way according to the browser''s standards. It also depends on the visitors Operating System (OS) and the visitor''s display resolution. <a href="http://kb.siteground.com/ " target="_blank">SiteGround KB</a> writes in a similar article <blockquote>"Web browsers do not render pages pixel by pixel. They read the entire code and produce an output depending on your code. There are, however, differences in the code interpretation. Therefore you should check the way your website looks on different browsers and operating systems."</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>This is definitely true in almost all cases. I cannot tell you how much trouble I have saved myself just by looking at my websites in multiple browsers. Especially when you are working on a prospective client''s website, you want to check the website''s compatibility before handing the keys over to them and risking the chance of them finding out you didn''t completely check their site for compatibility issues.</p>\r\n<h1>How can I overcome Cross-Compatible Web Design?</h1>\r\n<p>You can do what we were talking about above and that is by checking the website in multiple browsers. Oh I know, I found this tool for you that checks your website and displays it in multiple browsers. Here it is:\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<a href="http://www.browsershots.org" target="_blank">Browser Shots</a>\r\n<br /><br />\r\nAlthough overcoming this overwhelming issue isn''t solved with a simple yet complex website the checks your website in multiple browsers. Overcoming this obstacle starts with the way you write your code since a web browser interprets your code and produces an output based on what it reads. So naturally, purely changing your Web Design code-making skills up to match demands of popular web browsers would be the first step in overcoming this crisis that plagues most, if not all, web designers.\r\n</p>\r\n<h1>Why Google Chrome?</h1>\r\n<p>Finally, after exploring the ins and outs of Web Design can we now answer the sole question that this article is in-directly/directly talking about. Google Chrome comes equipped with a beautiful, functional, better Inspect Element module that allows you to control more aspects of your sites easily. Even though a majority of web browsers have this, Google Chrome actually does this more elegantly and more flawlessly as well. Google Chrome''s engine is designed to display websites the correct way by rendering them in a way unlike what most web browsers do. Chrome also has a minimalistic interface that doesn''t take up to much memory which would cause the page to load differently (faster). Other aspects of Google Chrome is the way most code looks, how the browser itself is much faster, there is a Large library of extensions and add-ons,  and the whole fact that you can go Incognito when browsing a page, which means for us web designers that no one can see what we are surfing.<br /><br />Here is a randomly-selected video on youtube, that I believe gets enough views to show you, that explains a bit more in detail (with video) the ends and outs of Google Chrome:\r\n[youtube id=1]TXC-pAk_tHE[/youtube]\r\n</p>\r\n<h1>Closing Remarks</h1>\r\n<p>In the end, does it really matter if I have a website that displays the same in all web browsers? Absolutely! Because of the way that a browser interprets your code and outputs based on that you must be one step ahead of the browser by tweaking your code and knowing how it displays so that you can make sure your websites load faster, better, and look nicer. Google Chrome makes browsing a dream and it just keeps getting better and better. I use Google Chrome myself to design (at least start out) all my websites and then move into looking at my design in other web browsers. In a way you could say that Google Chrome is my favorite web browser and I will continue to use it. So what are you waiting for? Go ahead and download a copy of <a href="https://www.google.com/intl/en/chrome/browser/ " target="_blank">Google Chrome</a> for FREE and see how much better it is when you design websites. Heck even if your surfing the web it is much better. Thanks for reading this post and have a blessed day!</p>', 1, 7, 'google chrome,chrome,design tips,design,using google chrome,web design,why chose google chrome,design,SiteGround KB,WYSIWYG,conditional CSS,SEO,Search Engine Optimization,Browser Shots,basis of web design,incognito,', '2012-09-21 17:30:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 2012, '09', '21', '17', '30', '00', 'yes', 'Published', 'yes', 'featured.jpg'),
(25, 'Back to the neverending grindstone', '<p>So guys, I know that I have not been posting any blogs for, well, 5 months now, but I have a legit excuse - I have been working on never-ending updates for this site. Such updates consisted of building this surely amazing and totally built-by-me cPanel, giving my site a complete make over, and just doing the normal, and totally not boring thing, of developing.</p>\r\n[!--more--]\r\n<h2>Life is tough</h2>\r\n<p>I know what you guys are thinking? "Why are you making your own site cPanel CMS when you could just use Wordpress?" Okay maybe that was too specific of a question, but the point is: I have been building me own CMS because it allows me to develop something and set goals for myself; despite all the headaches I have had just trying to get a damn $ variable to work with a certain insert_function_here(). This whole stuff fascinates me as a developer. From building something that is for the sole purpose of converting strings such as <b>open parenthesis</b> baseurl <b>closed parenthesis</b> (NOTE: I had to write it that way since If I chose to write it the correct way it will convert it like this\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<code>(baseurl)</code>\r\n<br /><br />\r\nSee that just gave us the base url of this site.) to completely getting a posting/editing/tweaking/building/managing cPanel system to fully work without having to access a single database. It''s tough. But oh so worth it. Just writing this content is tricky enough - there are certain things you must do in order to ensure posting of content to a database comes out sanitized and un-obstructive in the event some despicable hacker/leecher/breaker/terrorist comes along and injects your code with something malicious. Oh yeah, as a developer one must think like a hacker in order to prevent hacking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That being said, no one person is safe from malicious activity done to them. One must take all necessary provisions to "counter-hack and protect". For me, I am more of a 50/50 person when it comes to hacking. I wouldn''t be caught dead hacking a bank but I will hack my iPhone 4S iOS 6.0 to allow me to tweak it in a way that allows certain fun things to go on inside my phone. Like a party! Sorry, squirrel-moment. But if it''s one thing I have learned from developing is that you have to be one step ahead of the game.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>How''s life you say?</h2>\r\n<p>Not bad, just the normal usual development stuff I do everyday. I like to develop. In case you haven''t already figured that much out. If you haven''t heard, I now work at a fine institution called The Wedding Guide, once of the biggest Wedding companies in Austin and San Antonio, as a web assistant helping maintain web profiles, doing odd web work, and learning more commercial web stuff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am freakin amaZing! Why? Because I built future functionality into the posts/pages changer for sorts (sort by date, title, etc) and I am loving how I did that. Yeah, still coding here, making things happen! And look, I found a ghost variable. What is a ghost variable? I think I made it up. It is when a variable appears and you have no idea where it is coming from. Seriously, I checked the code and nothing resembles that. Weird.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>In the end...</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that the best part about being able to say that I made my own framework for my website is that I know how much effort goes into something like this. I will keep working on this site and it will soon become something amazing. Stay tuned for more from me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nathan</p>\r\n', 1, 1, 'grindstone,back,wedding guide,neverending,iphone,4s,apple,development,malicious,counter-hack,squirrel', '2013-02-13 22:14:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 2013, '02', '13', '22', '14', '35', 'yes', 'Published', 'yes', 'featured.jpg'),
